{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin | title=1922 general election: Yeovil <ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party =       Unionist Party (UK) \n |candidate =   [[Aubrey Herbert]]\n |votes =       15,468\n |percentage =  61.8\n |change =      +11.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party =       Labour Party (UK) \n |candidate =   [[William Kelly (Labour politician)|William Kelly]]\n |votes =       9,581\n |percentage =  38.3\n |change =      +1.9\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n |votes =     5,887  \n |percentage =  23.5\n |change =      +9.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes =       \n |percentage =  73.0\n |change =      +11.2\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Unionist Party (UK)\n |loser = \n |swing = +4.7\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n=== Elections in the 1910s ===\n[[File:Aubrey Herbert.jpg|thumb|120px|Aubrey Herbert]]\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1918 United Kingdom general election|General election 14 December 1918]]: Yeovil <ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link coalition 1918|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[Aubrey Herbert]]\n  |votes      =10,522\n  |percentage =50.5\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[William Kelly (Labour politician)|William Kelly]]\n  |votes      =7,589\n  |percentage =36.4\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = J. R. Brough\n  |votes      = 2,743\n  |percentage =13.2\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =2,933\n  |percentage =14.1\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =20,854\n  |percentage =61.8\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box new seat win|\n  |winner     = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |swing      =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box end 1918}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Parliamentary constituencies in Somerset]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Constituencies in South West England}}\n\n{{coord|50.9000|N|2.8100|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeovil (Uk Parliament Constituency)}}\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in Somerset]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Yeovil]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Constituency in South West England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency main\n |name        = Yeovil\n |parliament  = uk\n |map1        = Yeovil2007\n |map2        = EnglandSomerset\n |map_entity  = [[Somerset]]\n |map_year    = \n |year        = 1918\n |abolished   = \n |type        = County\n |elects_howmany = One\n |previous    = [[South Somerset (UK Parliament constituency)|South Somerset]] and [[East Somerset (UK Parliament constituency)|East Somerset]]\n |next        = \n |electorate  = 82,771 (December 2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boundarycommissionforengland.org.uk/electoral-figures/electoral-figures.htm|title=Electorate Figures&nbsp;\u2014 Boundary Commission for England|date=4 March 2011|work=2011 Electorate Figures|publisher=Boundary Commission for England|accessdate=13 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106204053/http://www.boundarycommissionforengland.org.uk/electoral-figures/electoral-figures.htm|archivedate=6 November 2010}}</ref>\n |mp          = [[Marcus Fysh]]\n |party       = Conservative Party (UK)\n |region      = England\n |county      = [[Somerset]]\n |european    = South West England\n}}\n'''Yeovil''' is a [[county constituency]] represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. It elects one [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) by the [[first past the post]] system of election. It has been represented since 2015 by [[Marcus Fysh]], a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]].\n\n== Boundaries ==\n'''1918\u20131974''': The Municipal Boroughs of Yeovil and Chard, the Urban Districts of Crewkerne and Ilminster, and the Rural Districts of Chard, Langport, and Yeovil.\n\n'''1974\u20131983''': As 1918 but with redrawn boundaries.\n\n'''1983\u20131997''': The District of Yeovil wards of Blackdown, Chard North East, Chard North West, Chard Parish, Chard South East, Chard South West, Chinnock, Coker, Crewkerne Town, Dowlish, Egwood, Hazelbury, Houndstone, Ilminster Town, Lynches, Mudford, Neroche, St Michael's, South Petherton, Stoke, Windwhistle, Yeovil Central, Yeovil East, Yeovil North, Yeovil Preston, Yeovil South, and Yeovil West.\n\n'''1997\u20132010''': The District of South Somerset wards of Blackdown, Chard Avishayes, Chard Combe, Chard Crimchard, Chard Holyrood, Chard Jocelyn, Coker, Crewkerne, Egwood, Hamdon, Houndstone, Ilminster, Mudford, Neroche, Parrett, St Michael's, South Petherton, Tatworth and Forton, Windwhistle, Yeovil Central, Yeovil East, Yeovil Preston, Yeovil South, Yeovil West, and Yeovil Without.\n\n'''2010\u2013present''': The District of South Somerset wards of Blackdown, Brympton, Chard Avishayes, Chard Combe, Chard Crimchard, Chard Holyrood, Chard Jocelyn, Coker, Crewkerne, Egwood, Hamdon, Ilminster, Ivelchester, Neroche, Parrett, St Michael's, South Petherton, Tatworth and Forton, Windwhistle, Yeovil Central, Yeovil East, Yeovil South, Yeovil West, and Yeovil Without.\n\nThe constituency covers the towns of [[Yeovil]], [[Chard, Somerset|Chard]], [[Crewkerne]] and [[Ilminster]] in [[Somerset]].  Until 1983 [[Somerset]] was split into four constituencies and Yeovil constituency also contained the towns of [[Ilchester]], [[Martock]] and [[Somerton, Somerset|Somerton]] but they were transferred to the newly created constituency of [[Somerton and Frome (UK Parliament constituency)|Somerton and Frome]].\n\nAs part of minor changes implemented following the review by the [[Boundary Commission for England]], the town of Ilchester was returned to the Yeovil constituency at the [[United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Fifth periodical report&nbsp;\u2014 Volume 4 Mapping for the Non-Metropolitan Counties and the Unitary Authorities|date=26 February 2007|publisher=The Stationery Office|ISBN=0-10-170322-8|url=http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm70/7032/7032_iv.asp}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nFrom 1918 until 1983, Yeovil always returned a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP (though by only narrow margins over [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] in the 1940s and 1950s).  There then followed a period of over 30 years during which the seat was represented by a member of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] or their successors, the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]; firstly former leader [[Paddy Ashdown]] (1983\u20132001) and then former Chief Secretary to the Treasury [[David Laws]] (2001 to 2015).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Yeovil|title=Yeovil|newspaper=Telegraph|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> At the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 election]], the seat returned to its former Conservative allegiance as [[Marcus Fysh]] defeated Laws by over 5,000 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14001060|title=Yeovil parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe South Somerset district voted 57% to leave the European Union, and academic analysis estimates that Yeovil itself voted 59% to leave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@chrishanretty/ward-level-results-from-the-eu-referendum-b9df8dd29c98|title=Ward level results from the EU referendum|first=Chris|last=Hanretty|date=6 February 2017|website=Medium}}</ref> There was a swing of 7.7% away from the pro-Remain Liberal Democrats towards the pro-Leave Conservatives, which made the seat much safer in 2017, Marcus Fysh's majority increasing to just under 15,000. In 2019 Fysh further increased his majority over the Liberal Democrat candidate to over 16,000 votes.\n\n== Members of Parliament ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Election!!Member<ref>{{cite web|title=Yeovil (UK Parliament Constituency)|url=http://www.altiusdirectory.com/UK/const_details.php?country=England&name=yeovil|publisher=Altius Directory|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n!Party\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n| [[Aubrey Herbert]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1923 Yeovil by-election|1923 by-election]]\n| [[George Davies (politician)|George Davies]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]\n| [[William Kingsmill (MP)|William Kingsmill]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1951 United Kingdom general election|1951]]\n| [[John Peyton, Baron Peyton of Yeovil|John Peyton]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Paddy Ashdown]]\n| [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| ''1988''\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\n| [[David Laws]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n| [[Marcus Fysh]]\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Elections ==\n=== Elections in the 2010s ===\n\n{{Election box begin|title=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|General election 2019]]: Yeovil<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southsomerset.go