-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| population_blank1_title         = Metro Rank\n| population_blank1               = [[List of metropolitan areas in Pakistan|8th, Pakistan]]\n| population_blank2_title         = [[Demonym]]\n| population_blank2               = Sargodhian\n| timezone1                       = [[Pakistan Standard Time|PST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in Pakistan|Postal code]]\n| postal_code                     = 40100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakpost.gov.pk/postcode/postcode.html|title=Pakistan Post Office Department|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=12 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111220155725/http://www.pakpost.gov.pk/postcode/postcode.html|archivedate=20 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| area_code_type                  = [[Dialling codes in Pakistan|Dialling code]]\n| area_code                       = 048<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptcl.com.pk/Info/National-Dialing-Codes|title=National Dialing Codes|website=Ptcl.com.pk|accessdate=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109145658/http://www.ptcl.com.pk/Info/National-Dialing-Codes|archive-date=9 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| blank_name_sec2                 = Number of [[Union councils of Pakistan|union councils]]\n| blank_info_sec2                 = 22\n| blank1_name_sec2                = Number of [[town]]s\n| blank1_info_sec2                = 59\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.sargodha.gop.pk/}}; {{URL|http://cbs.gov.pk/}}; {{URL|http://www.tmasargodha.com/}}\n| official_name                   = \n| nickname                        = City of Eagles<ref>http://visitpak.com/useful-info-about-sargodha-pakistan-the-city-of-eagles/</ref>\n| governing_body                  = \n| image_seal                      = \n| image_flag                      = Flag of Punjab.svg\n| image_blank_emblem              = CBS logo.jpg\n| leader_party                    = \n| blank_emblem_type               = [[Sargodha Cantonment|CBS]] logo\n| blank_emblem_size               = 50px\n}}\n\n'''Sargodha''' ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u0631\u06af\u0648\u062f\u06be\u0627}}}}) is the [[List of most populous cities in Pakistan|11th largest]] city in [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"citypopulation.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Pakistan-100T.html|title=Pakistan: Provinces and Major Cities \u2013 Population Statistics, Maps, Charts, Weather and Web Information|website=Citypopulation.de}}</ref> It is also an administrative centre of [[Sargodha Division]] located in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province, Pakistan and one of the fastest growing cities in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ghar47.com/2015/07/05/commercial-real-estate-property-in-sargodha-pakistan/|title=Commercial Real Estate Property in Sargodha Pakistan \u2013 Ghar47|work=Ghar47|accessdate=12 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216175421/http://ghar47.com/2015/07/05/commercial-real-estate-property-in-sargodha-pakistan/|archivedate=16 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sargodha is also known as ''City of Eagles''.<ref>http://visitpak.com/useful-info-about-sargodha-pakistan-the-city-of-eagles/</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==History==\nSargodha was established by the British as a canal-colony in 1903, and was initially spelt Sargoda.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wkBuAAAAMAAJ&q=sargodha+history+1903&dq=sargodha+history+1903&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUkMy77KzZAhVkHGMKHcVgCvgQ6AEIKTAB|title=Pakistan: a historical and cultural panorama|last=Masud|first=Tariq|date=1989|publisher=Al-Waqar Publishers|isbn=9789698054021|language=en}}</ref> Sargodha was badly affected by an outbreak of the plague in 1903, and experienced a milder outbreak in 1904.<ref name=\"Cell Cell 2002 p. \">{{cite book | last=Cell | first=J.W. | last2=Cell | first2=J.W. | title=Hailey: A Study in British Imperialism, 1872-1969 | publisher=Cambridge University Press | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-521-52117-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K5LX9AUcyMYC | access-date=2020-04-09 | page=}}</ref> Although it was a small town in the beginning, the British [[Royal Air Force]] built an airport here due to its strategic location.<ref name=\"sargodha.dc.lhc.gov.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://sargodha.dc.lhc.gov.pk/?page_id=1335|title=District Website|website=Lhc.gov.pk}}</ref>\nThe term \u201cSargodha\u201d has its origin in the words \u201cSar\u201d meaning \u201cpond\u201d and \u201cGodha\u201d meaning \u201cSadhu\u201d, which means \u201cPond of Godha\u201d. This city was founded by Lady Trooper by the supervision of Sir [[Charles Montgomery Rivaz]] KCSI (1845 - 7 October 1926) was a colonial administrator in British India, and Lieutenant-Governor of the Punjab 1902-1907.<ref>http://sargodha.dc.lhc.gov.pk/PublicPages/HistoryOfDistrict.aspx</ref>.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_governors_of_Punjab_(British_India)</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n===Location===\n\nLocation of Sargodha with respect to five major cities of Pakistan is as follow:\n*{{cvt|1202|km}} North of [[Karachi]]<ref>https://www.rome2rio.com/s/Karachi/Sargodha</ref>\n*{{cvt|187|km}} West of [[Lahore]]<ref>https://www.distancecalculator.net/from-lahore-to-sargodha</ref>\n*{{cvt|241|km}} South of [[Islamabad]]<ref>https://www.distancesto.com/road-map/pk/sargodha-to-islamabad/history/598090.html</ref>\n*{{cvt|91|km}} North-West of [[Faisalabad]]<ref>http://pk.toponavi.com/66794-66792</ref>\n*{{cvt|223|km}} South of [[Rawalpindi]]<ref>https://www.distancecalculator.net/from-rawalpindi-to-sargodha</ref>\n\nSargodha is situated in Pakistani province of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]. It is located {{convert|187|km}} northwest of [[Lahore]], in [[Sargodha District]].<ref>https://www.distancecalculator.net/from-lahore-to-sargodha</ref> It lies about {{convert|30|mile|order=flip}} from the M-2 motorway, which connects [[Lahore]] and [[Islamabad]]. It is connected to the M-2 by several interchanges at different locations. Sargodha is roughly {{cvt|91|km}} from [[Faisalabad]], due southeast.<ref>http://pk.toponavi.com/66794-66792</ref> Directly east connected by the M-2 motorway are Lahore and the route to [[Rawalpindi]] and [[Islamabad]]. Due east is the city of [[Jhang]]; toward the west are the city of [[Mianwali]] and the Chashma Barrage.\n\n===Topography===\nSargodha mainly comprises flat, fertile plains, although here are a few small hills on the Sargodha-Faisalabad Road. The River Jhelum flows on the western and northern sides, and the River [[Chenab]] lies on the eastern side of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sargodha.gop.pk/district-at-glance|title=District at Glance|work=sargodha.gop.pk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626122455/http://www.sargodha.gop.pk/district-at-glance|archivedate=26 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The city is located 190 metres above sea level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/as/pk/pb/where-is-sargodha.html|title=Where is Sargodha, Pakistan?|website=WorldAtlas.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nThe city has a climate of extreme heat in the summers and moderate cold in the winters. The maximum temperature reaches {{convert|50|C}} in the summer while the minimum temperature recorded is as low as freezing point in the winter.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location     = Sargodha (1960\u20132012)\n| metric first = y\n| single line  = y\n| Jan high C = 20\n| Feb high C = 22\n| Mar high C = 26\n| Apr high C = 32\n| May high C = 38\n| Jun high C = 39\n| Jul high C = 38\n| Aug high C = 37\n| Sep high C = 36\n| Oct high C = 32\n| Nov high C = 26\n| Dec high C = 22\n| year high C = 30.6\n| Jan low C = 8\n| Feb low C = 11\n| Mar low C = 15.5\n| Apr low C = 19\n| May low C = 25\n| Jun low C = 27\n| Jul low C = 26\n| Aug low C = 26\n| Sep low C = 25\n| Oct low C = 20\n| Nov low C = 14\n| Dec low C = 9\n| year low C = 18.8\n| Jan precipitation mm = 18\n| Feb precipitation mm = 36\n| Mar precipitation mm = 24\n| Apr precipitation mm = 13\n| May precipitation mm = 17\n| Jun precipitation mm = 48\n| Jul precipitation mm = 82\n| Aug precipitation mm = 87\n| Sep precipitation mm = 43\n| Oct precipitation mm = 9\n| Nov precipitation mm = 11\n| Dec precipitation mm = 12\n| Jan precipitation days = 5\n| Feb precipitation days = 4\n| Mar precipitation days = 5\n| Apr precipitation days = 4\n| May precipitation days = 3\n| Jun precipitation days = 3\n| Jul precipitation days = 7\n| Aug precipitation days = 7\n| Sep precipitation days = 4\n| Oct precipitation days = 1\n| Nov precipitation days = 1\n| Dec precipitation days = 1\n| unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n| source 1                = Weather2,<ref name = Weather2>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.myweather2.com/City-Town/Pakistan/Sargodha/climate-profile.aspx\n  | title = Weather2 \u2013 Sargodha\n  | accessdate =8 July 2012\n}}</ref>\n| date                    = August 2010\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\nTotal population of the city was 458,440<ref name=\"census.gov.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.gov.pk/sites/default/files//tables/POPULATION%20SIZE%20AND%20GROWTH%20OF%20MAJOR%20CITIES.pdf |title=Population size and growth of major cities |publisher=[[Pakistan Bureau of Statistics]] |date=1998}}</ref> according to the 1998 census.  The majority of the people in the city speak [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]].<ref name=\"sargodha.dc.lhc.gov.pk\"/> According to the [[2017 Census of Pakistan]], the population of City was recorded 872,557 with the rise of 43.94% while the population of metropolitan area (City District) reached 3,903,588 out of which 1 million forms the urban population.<ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|access-date=2017-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> The population of [[Sargodha Division]] was recorded as 8,181,499 as per [[2017 Census of Pakistan]].\n\n==Economy==\nMajority of economy of Sargodha depends upon agriculture. Sargodha is considered as the best citrus producing area of Pakistan and therefore, it is also known as [[California]] of Pakistan.<ref>www.historypak.com/sargodha/</ref> Sargodha is largest [[Kinnow]] producing district of the world. It produces best quality oranges and supply to the different parts of the country. These oranges are also exported to other countries and contributes to the economy of Pakistan.<ref>https://www.academia.edu/7790985/Orange_Economy_of_Sargodha</ref> Sargodha also produces a huge amount of wheat, cotton, rice and vegetables that are transported to other parts of country and also exported to other countries. \n\nThere are also Textile mills, Rice processing plants and juice factories of [[Nestle]] and [[Shezan]].<ref>www.historypak.com/sargodha/</ref>\n\nThe Sargodha Chamber of Commerce and Industry monitors industrial activity in the city and reports their findings to the [[Federation of Pakistan Chamber of Commerce and Industry]] and provincial government.<ref>https://www.scci.pk</ref> Dry port is also under construction in Sargodha.<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1111172/facilitating-exports-dry-port-established-sargodha/</ref>\n\nThere are also several shopping malls and trade centres in the city that have a presence of international and national brands. Some of them are as follow:<ref>\nhttp://www.mallofsargodha.com</ref>\n[[File:Mall of Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Mall of Sargodha under construction]]\n[[File:Burj Ismail Mall Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Burj Ismail Mall]]\n\n*Mall of Sargodha\n*Burj Ismail Mall\n*Chenone Tower\n*Rehman Trade Centre\n*Burj Huraira Mall\n*Trust Plaza\n*Galaxy Mobile Tower\n*Toheed Mall\n*Apna Cash & Carry\n*Dreamland Shopping Mall\n*Shaheen Shopping Mall\n*Modern Shopping Mall\n*Punjab Mega Mall\n\nFifteen bazaars (markets) of Sargodha remain a major trading zone in the city. Each of the fifteen bazaars has a particular name and is known for selling certain goods as follows:<ref>https://pmbmc.punjab.gov.pk/sargodha</ref><ref name=\"urbanunit.gov.pk\">http://www.urbanunit.gov.pk/PublicationDocs/Punjab%20city%20profiles/Sargodha%20City%20Profile.pdf</ref>\n*Model Bazaar contains food court, joyland and shops of grocery and garments.\n*Urdu Bazaar contains shops of stationery and books.\n*Kachehry Bazaar contains bakeries, street food restaurants and shops of shoes, garments and general stores.\n*Amin Bazaar contains shops of fabrics, boutique], garments and electric appliances.\n*Muslim Bazaar contains sanitary items and motorcycle repair shops.\n*Anarkali Bazaar contains shops of each and every household items.\n*Sarafa Bazaar contains gold and jewellery shops.\n*Rail Bazaar contains shops of fabrics.\n*Liaquat Bazaar provides shops for new bicycles and sports cycles.\n*Faisal Bazar provides shops for spices, oil, meat and poultry.\n*Karkhana Bazaar provides shops for crockery and cutlery products.\n*Bans Bazaar supplies dairy and milk products.\n*Kabaarhi Bazaar contains shops of [[brokers]].\n*Fruit Mandi is a fruit market.\n*Sabzi Mandi is a vegetable, meat, fish and grocery market.\n\n==Administration==\nSargodha is the capital of [[Sargodha Tehsil]]. As of October 2012, the division system in Punjab Province has been restored and Sargodha became the divisional headquarters of districts [[Sargodha District|Sargodha]], [[Khushab District|Khushab]], [[Mianwali District|Mianwali]] and [[Bhakkar District|Bhakkar]]. Sargodha became the administrative capital of the [[Sargodha Division]] handling over a population of about 8.1 Million.<ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|access-date=2017-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Municipal Committee of Sargodha city was upgraded into Municipal Corporation in 1981 when the population of city was increased over half a million.<ref>http://tmasargodha.lgpunjab.org.pk</ref> In December 2019, Sargodha Municipal Corporation was upgraded into Metropolitan Corporation under Punjab Local Government Act 2019.<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/1524621</ref>\n\n===Safe City Project===\n\nSargodha was announced as one of six cities in Punjab whose security would be improved by the [[Punjab Safe Cities Authority]]. 5.5 billion Rupees have been allocated for the project,<ref>{{cite news|title=After Lahore, six others to become 'safer cities'|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1332499/lahore-six-others-become-safer-cities/|accessdate=23 February 2017|agency=Express Tribune|date=20 February 2017}}</ref> which will be modeled along the lines of the Lahore Safe City project in which 8,000 [[CCTV]] cameras were installed throughout the city at a cost of 12 billion rupees to record and send images to Integrated Command and Control Centres.<ref>{{cite news|title=Punjab Safe City Project inaugurated|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1289650|accessdate=23 February 2017|agency=Dawn|date=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Health==\n{{Main|List of hospitals in Sargodha}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n=== Hospitals===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n!Hospital<ref>https://www.marham.pk/hospitals/sargodha</ref>\n!Type\n!Location\n|-\n| [[Combined Military Hospital]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Sargodha Garrison\n|-\n| [[Civil Hospital|DHQ Teaching Hospital]]\n| [[Public]]\n| [[Mianwali]] Road\n|-\n| [[PAF Hospitals|PAF Hospital]]\n| [[Air force]]\n| [[PAF Base Mushaf]]\n|-\n| [[Fauji Foundation|Fauji Foundation Hospital]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| [[Hilal Ahmar|Halal-e-Ahmar Hospital]]\n| [[Public]]\n| Satellite Town B-Block\n|-\n| [[University of Sargodha|University Medical and Research Centre]]\n| [[Public]]\n| [[University of Sargodha]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Education==\n[[File:UoS.jpg|thumb|Main Gate to University of Sargodha]]\n[[File:PAF Public School Sargodha HQ 2003.jpg|thumb|PAF Public School]]\n\nAccording to the census of 1998, the literacy rate of Sargodha city was 67.8% while in 2017 the literacy rate was recorded as 80.5% with a rapid increase in few years.<ref>https://www.urbanunit.gov.pk \u203a ...PDF\nSargodha City Profile \u2013 The Urban Unit</ref> The city is considered as the educational hub of Sargodha Division handling the population of about 8.1 million.<ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|access-date=2017-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Sargodha Division]] has its own Education Board for Secondary School Certificate (SSC) & Higher Secondary School Certificate (HSSC) Examinations. There are about 4 universities and numerous colleges of Medical Sciences, Law, IT, Commerce, Engineering and Intermediate Courses.\n\n=== Board of Intermediate and Secondary Education Sargodha ===\nBoard of Intermediate & Secondary Education, Sargodha<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bisesargodha.edu.pk|title=BISE SARGODHA}}</ref> handles the whole Sargodha Division that includes 4 districts (Sargodha, Mianwali, Khushab & Bhakkar). It was established in 1968 under the West Pakistan Board of Intermediate & Secondary Education ([[Board of Intermediate and Secondary Education, Multan|Multan]] and [[Board of Intermediate and Secondary Education, Sargodha]]) Ordinance No. VII of 1968, with the jurisdiction of Sargodha and Rawalpindi Civil Divisions.\n\n=== Educational institutes ===\n{{Main|List of educational institutes in Sargodha}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! University/College\n! Type\n! Location\n! Established\n! Website\n|-\n| [[University of Sargodha]]\n| [[Public]]\n| University Road\n| 2002\n|<ref>https://www.uos.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| [[University College of Agriculture]]\n| [[Public]]\n| Sargodha Bypass near Jhal Chakian\n| 2002\n|-\n| [[University of Lahore|University of Lahore, Sargodha Campus]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Lahore Road\n| 2002\n|<ref>https://www.uol.edu.pk/about-us</ref>\n|-\n| [[University of Central Punjab|University of Central Punjab, Sargodha Campus]]\n|[[Private university|Private]]\n|Lahore Road\n|2002\n|<ref>https://www.ucp.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sargodha Medical College]]\n| [[Public]]\n| Faisalabad Road\n| 2006\n|<ref>https://www.uos.edu.pk/department/profile/14</ref>\n|-\n| [[Army Public Schools & Colleges System|Army Public College]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Mianwali Road\n| 1975\n|-\n| [[PAF College Sargodha|PAF College]]\n| [[Air force]]\n| [[PAF Base Mushaf]]\n| 1953\n| <ref>{{url|http://www.pafcollegesargodha.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Cornelius Law College]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Fatima Jinnah Road\n| 2015\n|<ref>http://pu.edu.pk/affiliation/collegeinfo/1270/Cornelius-Law-College-Lahore-Road-Sargodha</ref>\n|-\n| [[Quaid-e-Azam Law College]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Lahore Road\n| 1998 \n|<ref>https://qlc.edu.pk/sargodha-campus/</ref>\n|-\n| [[Punjab College of Science]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Khayaban-e-Sadiq (Main Campus)\n| 1985\n|<ref>https://www.pgc.edu/about-pgc</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Superior College]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n| 2000\n|<ref>https://superiorcolleges.edu.pk/sargodha/</ref>                            \n|-\n| [[Dar-e-Arqam Schools|Dar-e-Arqam College]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n| 2002\n| <ref>https://www.das.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sargodha Institute of Technology]]\n| \n| University Road\n| 1927\n|-\n| [[American Lycetuff|American Lycetuff School]]\n| Private\n| Queens Road\n| 1996\n|-\n| [[Roots Millennium Schools|Root Millennium School]]\n| Private\n| Queens Road\n| 1988\n|<ref>[http://www.millenniumschools.edu.pk/aboutrms.php \"About Roots Millennium Schools\".] Retrieved on 26 February 2015.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Beaconhouse School System]]\n| Private\n| University Road\n| 1975\n| <ref>{{URL|www.beaconhouse.net}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The City School (Pakistan)|The City School]]\n| Private\n| Queens Road\n| 1978\n| <ref>https://thecityschool.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| [[Lahore Grammar School]]\n| Private\n| [[Mushaf Ali Mir]] Road\n| 1979\n|-\n| [[Army Public Schools & Colleges System|Army Public School]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Mianwali Road\n| 1975\n|-\n| [[Fauji Foundation|Fauji Foundation School]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Civil Lines\n| 1954\n| <ref>{{url|http://www.fauji.org.pk/}}\n}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Allied Schools (Pakistan)|Allied School]]\n| Private\n| Main Garden Town Road\n| 1985\n| <ref>https://alliedschools.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Transportation==\n===Road===\n[[File:University Road, Sargodha.jpg|thumb|University Road, Sargodha]]\n[[File:Khayyam Chowk Flyover Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Khayyam Chowk Flyover]]\n\n====Roads abd flyovers====\n4 km long University Roads runs from 47 Pull to Khayyam Chowk. Other main roads include 6 km long Fatima Jinnah Road, City Road, Canal Road, Katchery Road, Stadium Road, Club Road, Jail Road, Queens Road, Mushaf Ali Mir Road, Railway Road, Lahore Road, Faisalabad Road, Eid Gah Road, Mianwali Road, Sillanwali Road, Bhalwal Road and Shaheenabad Road etc. There are 3 flyovers in the city area to regulate the traffic, Khayyam Chowk flyover has a length of 1 km and it starts from Khayyam Chowk and leds to Mianwali Road, Fatima Jinnah Road flyover is also 1 km long, 0.4 km long flyover is located on Kachehry Road.\n\n====Motorways and highways====\n[[File: M2 Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Motorway M2 exit to Sargodha]]\n\nSargodha lies about {{Convert|30|mi|km}} from the [[M-2 motorway (Pakistan)|M-2 Motorway]] which connects Lahore and [[Islamabad]]. [[N-60 National Highway]] runs from Sargodha to Lahore through [[Pindi Bhattian]] and [[Sheikhupura]]. It is also connected to Faisalabad by a highway.\n\n===Buses===\n\nGeneral Bus Stand is located on Fatima Jinnah Road that provides bus service from Sargodha to almost every part of the country. [[Daewoo Express|Daewoo Bus Service]] drives regular routes from Sargodha to the rest of the country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.daewoo.com.pk/terminal_view.asp?menu_set=5&submenu_set=1&page_title=Sargodha&terminal_code=13 |title=Archived copy |access-date=6 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706175300/http://www.daewoo.com.pk/terminal_view.asp?menu_set=5&submenu_set=1&page_title=Sargodha&terminal_code=13 |archive-date=6 July 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Others include Niazi Express, Faisal Movers, Bilal Travels, Islamabad Express and Skyways etc.\n\n===Taxi and Rickshaws===\n\nOnline cab services [[Uber]] and [[Careem]] are also available in the city.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.careem.com/en-ae/cities/|title=Countries of Operation|language=en}}</ref> Moreover many Rickshaws are also available throughout the city which are more economical.\n\n===Rail===\nSargodha is also connected by the rest of the country through the rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railpk.com/sarghodha.html|title=Pakistan Railway Time Table|work=railpk.com}}</ref> [[Sargodha Junction railway station]] is located on Shorkot-Lala Musa branch railway line.\n\n== Air Base==\nPakistan's largest [[airbase]], [[PAF Base Mushaf]] (formerly PAF Base Sargodha), is situated in Sargodha and hosts the headquarters of the [[Pakistan Air Force]]'s Central Air Command. The airbase is also home to the Combat Commanders School (CCS), formerly the Fighter Leader's School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glowpakistan.com/about-pakistan/About-Sargodha-292|title=About Sargodha|work=glowpakistan.com}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation==\n===Points of interest===\n\n====Kirana Hills====\nThe [[Kirana Hills]] is a small and extensive rocky [[mountain range]] located in Sargodha.<ref>{{harv|Mahajan|2009|pp=100\u2013110}}</ref><ref>{{harv|Ali|2002|pp=25\u201326}}</ref><ref>{{harv|Smith|2007|pp=92\u201393}}</ref><ref name=Wikimaps>{{cite web |last1=Wikimaps |title=Kirana Hills |url=http://wikimapia.org/12771852/Kirana-Hills |website=Wikimapia.org |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> It is also a place of tourist attraction in Sargodha City. Locally known as \"'''Black Mountains'''\"<ref name=\"Bahria University press\">{{cite web |last1=DoE&ES |first1=Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences |title=Special report: Field report on Kirana Hills |url=http://www.slideshare.net/chsabasaif/slideshare-29477895 |publisher=Bahria University Press |accessdate=15 June 2015 |location=Karachi, Sindh, Pakistan |pages=33 |language=English |format=.net| ref = harv |date=2012}}</ref> due to its [[Bistre|brownish landscape]], its highest peak is about {{convert|980|ft|m}}.<ref>{{harv|DoE&ES|2012|pp=4\u20135}}</ref>\n\n====Jinnah Hall====\n\n[[Jinnah Hall]] is a historical landmark and point of interest in Sargodha.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Jinnah+Hall/@32.0830934,72.6661648,15z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0xcf178cb476e5cada?sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3io3WjJTPAhVFExoKHSyXAbUQ_BIIYTAO |title=Google Maps |website=Google.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-17}}</ref> Jinnah Hall was built in 1949. It was named for the Founder of Pakistan, [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]. Jinnah Hall was built originally as a town hall and library in Company Bagh, Sargodha but now currently used as an exhibition hall, event space, and library.\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:Kirana Hills Lake Sargodha.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Lake of Kirana Hills.]]\n| [[File:Jinnah Hall Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Jinnah Hall, Sargodha.]]\n|}\n\n===Sports===\n\nSargodha is home to the [[Sargodha Cricket Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/ground/59014.html|title=Sports Stadium \u2013 Pakistan \u2013 Cricket Grounds \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo}}</ref> Sargodha cricket team were a first-class cricket team that represented Sargodha Division in Punjab Province in Pakistan. They competed in Pakistan's first-class tournaments between 1961\u201362 and 2002\u201303. \n\n[[Mela Mandi Ground]] is a multi-use historic stadium in Sargodha.  It is currently used mostly for [[cricket]] and [[football (soccer)|football]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Mela+Mandi+Ground/@32.0691594,72.6590951,15z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x3d77fd98247eb21f!8m2!3d32.0691594!4d72.6590951%3C|title=Google Maps|website=Google Maps}}</ref> The Mela Mandi Ground was constructed to provide a vast ground for outdoor sports and activities. During March every year which is the country's spring season, several competitions are held here. Almost all Pakistani people join these annual games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flighthub.com/cheap-flights-to-Sargodha|title=Cheap flights to Sargodha|website=Flighthub.com}}</ref>\n\nSargodha is also home to Sargodha Astroturf Hockey Stadium located near Mela Mandi Ground. It is home to Sargodha District Hockey Team and provides a reliable platform for youngsters.<ref>https://www.urdupoint.com/en/sports/trials-for-hockey-team-selection-at-astroturf-539537.html</ref> Galaxy Sports Complex is a renowned Sports Academy of the city. <ref>http://wikimapia.org/3443348/Galaxy-ground</ref>\n\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:Hockey Stadium Sargodha.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|Sargodha Astroturf Hockey Stadium]]\n| [[File:Mela Mandi Ground Sargodha.jpg|thumb|upright=.75|Annual Tent Pegging Competition, Mela Mandi Ground]]\n|}\n\n==Food and drink==\n\n===Traditional food and drink===\n\nCuisine of Sargodha is similar to that of other regions of South Asia, with some of it being originated from the royal kitchens of 16th-century Mughal emperors.<ref name=\"Goodwin2002\">{{cite book|last=Goodwin|first=William|title=Pakistan|year=2002|publisher=Lucent Books|language=English|isbn=978-1-59018-218-5|page=79|quote=Pakistani food is similar to that of northern India, with a splash of Middle Eastern influence derived from other Muslim cultures over the centuries.}}</ref> Most of those dishes have their roots in [[British cuisine|British]], [[Indian cuisine|Indian]], [[Central Asian cuisine|Central Asian]] and [[Middle Eastern cuisine]].<ref name=\"LeeNadeau2011\">{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Jonathan H.X.|last2=Nadeau|first2=Kathleen M.|title=Encyclopedia of Asian American Folklore and Folklife|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|language=English|isbn=978-0-313-35066-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofas00leej/page/973 973]|quote=Pakistani cuisine\u2014a fusion of Central Asian, Middle Eastern, Persian, and Indian traditions\u2014is known for being spicy and for its aromatic and flavorful richness.|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofas00leej/page/973}}</ref> Unlike Middle Eastern cuisine, Pakistani cooking uses large quantities of spices, herbs, and seasoning. Garlic, [[ginger]], [[turmeric]], red [[Chili powder|chili]], and [[garam masala]] are used in most dishes, and home cooking regularly includes curry, [[pita bread|''roti'']], a thin flatbread made from wheat, is a staple food, usually served with curry, meat, vegetables, and lentils. Rice is also common; it is served plain, fried with spices, and in sweet dishes.<ref name=\"yasmeen\">{{cite book |author=Yasmeen Niaz Mohiuddin |title=Pakistan: a global studies handbook |year=2006 |publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-801-9|pages=3, 317, 323\u2013324}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Kathleen W. Deady |title=Countries of the world :Pakistan |year=2001 |publisher=Capstone Press |isbn=978-0-7368-0815-6 |pages=13\u201315}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=American Geriatrics Society. Ethnogeriatrics Committee |title=Doorway thoughts: cross-cultural health care for older adults |year=2006 |publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning |isbn=978-0-7637-4355-0 |pages=119\u2013120}}</ref>\n\n[[Lassi]] is a traditional drink in the whole [[Punjab region]] including Sargodha Division. [[Pakistani tea culture|Black tea with milk and sugar]] is also popular throughout the city and is consumed daily by most of the population.<ref name=\"taxila\">{{cite book |title=Pakistan & the Karakoram Highway |year=2008 |publisher=Lonely Planet |isbn=978-1-74104-542-0 |pages=60, 128, 376 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zn8I4qEew9oC|author1=Sarina Singh |author2=Lindsay Brow |author3=Paul Clammer |author4=Rodney Cocks |author5=John Mock}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Tarla Dalal |title=Punjabi Khana |year=2007 |publisher=Sanjay & Co |isbn=978-81-89491-54-3 |page=8}}</ref>\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n|[[File:Chili Chutney Restaurant Sargodha.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|A local restaurant, Sargodha]]\n|[[File:Food street Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Food Street on Stadium Road, Sargodha.]]\n|}\n\n===Fast Food===\n\nIn addition to the traditional food, fast food is also very famous across the city.<ref>https://nation.com.pk/17-Dec-2017/the-fried-chicken-turnaround</ref> Along with local fast food restaurants, there is also a presence of outlets of many International Fast Food Restaurants in the city that includes [[KFC]], [[McDonald's]] and [[Pizza Hut]].<ref>https://www.kfcpakistan.com</ref><ref>https://mcdonalds.com.pk</ref><ref>https://www.pizzahut.com.pk</ref>\n\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n|[[File:McDonald's Sargodha.jpg|thumb|[[McDonald's]], Sargodha]]\n|[[File:KFC Sargodha.jpg|thumb|[[KFC]], University Road, Sargodha]]\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n{{sisterlinks|Sargodha}}\n* [[Ali Haider Noor Khan Niazi]], politician \n* [[Feroz Khan Noon]], former [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister Pakistan]]\n* [[Anwer Ali Noon]], former Parliamentarian of Pakistan and army Officer\n* [[Amjad Ali Noon]], former Ambassador/High Commissioner of Pakistan\n* [[Imtiaz Bhatti]], former Ambassador / High Commissioner of Pakistan\n* [[Wazir Agha]], Urdu Scholar\n* [[Hameed Gul]], former ISI Chief\n* [[Ch. Anwar Ali Cheema]], politician, PML-Q\n* Ch.[[Ghias Mela]], politician, PML-Q\n* [[Hafiz Muhammad Saeed]], Amir [[Jama'at-ud-Da'wah]]\n* [[Mohammad Hafeez]], cricketer\n* [[Aizaz Cheema]], cricketer\n* [[Rafiq Anjum]], actor\n* [[Farhat Hashmi]], Islamic Scholar\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Sargodha}}\n\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Planned cities in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sargodha]]\n", "name_user": "Clever Boiiii", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEconomy)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sargodha"}
{"title_page": "I\u00f1aki Williams", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|Williams|Arthuer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = I\u00f1aki Williams\n| image = File:3 de diciembre 2015 Bienvenida al Atlethic de Bilbao 11 (23388774212) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Williams in 2015\n| fullname = I\u00f1aki Williams Arthuer\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1994|6|15|df=y}}<ref name=Bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/inaki-williams_prs413750/person.shtml|title=I\u00f1aki Williams|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Bilbao]], Spain<ref name=Bio/>\n| height = 1.86 m<ref name=Bio/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Athletic Bilbao]]\n| clubnumber = 9\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Nataci\u00f3n Pamplona\n| youthyears2 = 2009\u20132012 | youthclubs2 = [[CD Pamplona|Pamplona]]\n| youthyears3 = 2012\u20132013 | youthclubs3 = [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|Athletic Bilbao]]\n| years1 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs1 = [[CD Basconia|Basconia]] | caps1 = 18 | goals1 = 7\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs2 = [[Athletic Bilbao B|Bilbao Athletic]] | caps2 = 32 | goals2 = 21\n| years3 = 2014\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] | caps3 = 185 | goals3 = 40\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\u20132017 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 17 | nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2016\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2018\u2013 | nationalteam3 = [[Basque Country national football team|Basque Country]] | nationalcaps3 = 1 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| club-update = 11:20, 9 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 12 October 2018\n}}\n\n'''I\u00f1aki Williams Arthuer''' ({{IPA-eu|i\u0272aki wilians\u033a|lang}}; {{IPA-es|i\u02c8\u0272aki \u02c8wiljans|lang}}; born 15 June 1994) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Athletic Bilbao]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://larepublica.es/2015/05/07/inaki-williams-la-pantera-de-lezama/|title=I\u00f1aki Williams, la pantera de Lezama|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams, Lezama's panther|newspaper=La Rep\u00fablica|first=\u00cd\u00f1igo|last=Renedo|language=es|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=16 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812064446/http://larepublica.es/2015/05/07/inaki-williams-la-pantera-de-lezama/|archivedate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Bilbao]], [[Biscay]] to Ghanaian parents (that crossed the desert on foot and jumped the [[Melilla border fence]] to reach Spain),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://athletic.elcorreo.com/inaki-williams-millones-20190514070954-nt.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams: \u00abTengo entre 5 y 10 millones de euros\u00bb|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams: \"I have between 5 and 10 million euros\"|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|first=Silvia|last=Cantera|language=es|date=14 May 2019|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref> Williams spent much of his childhood in [[Pamplona]]<ref name=Correo>{{cite news|url=http://www.elcorreo.com/vizcaya/v/20131015/deportes/mas-baloncesto/inaki-williams-regresa-20131015.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams regresa con gol|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams returns with a goal|newspaper=El Correo|language=es|date=15 October 2013|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://athletic.elcorreo.com/discurso-williams-viral-negro-vasco-20180809175944-nt.html|title=El discurso de Williams que todo el mundo elogia: \u00abSoy negro, pero tambi\u00e9n vasco\u00bb|trans-title=The Williams speech that everyone praises: \"I am black, but also Basque\"|newspaper=El Correo|language=es|date=9 August 2018|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> and was playing youth football with local [[CD Pamplona]] when he was spotted by [[Athletic Bilbao]], who signed him to their youth setup at [[Lezama Facilities|Lezama]] at the age of 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.naiz.eus/es/blogs/marakanatxikia/posts/black-is-basque|title=Black is Basque|newspaper=Naiz|language=es|date=21 January 2016|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> He spent his first season with the ''[[Athletic Bilbao Juvenil|Juvenil A]]'' side and made a big impression, scoring at the rate of almost a goal a game (eventually ending with 36); the team [[2013 Copa del Rey Juvenil|finished runners-up]] in the [[Copa del Rey Juvenil de F\u00fatbol]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/06/29/futbol/cantera/1372536912.html|title=El Madrid gana la Copa juvenil veinte a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s|trans-title=Madrid win the 'Copa Juvenil' after 20 years|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=29 June 2013|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref> and on 25 June 2013 he signed a new contract with the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] club, running until 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2013/06/25/primera/1372176628_898059.html|title=El Athletic blinda a una de sus joyas del juvenil: I\u00f1aki Williams|trans-title=Athletic shield one of their youth squad gems: I\u00f1aki Williams|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Nika|last=Cuenca|language=es|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWilliams began [[2013\u201314 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2013\u201314]] playing with [[CD Basconia]], the [[farm team]] who competed in [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]. After suffering a knee injury in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://athletic.elcorreo.com/noticias/2013-08-15/inaki-williams-meses-baja-20130815.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams, de 2 a 5 meses de baja|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams, from 2 to 5 months out|newspaper=El Correo|language=es|date=15 August 2013|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> he returned to activity in October, made his debut as a senior and marked it with a goal.<ref name=Correo/> He was immediately called upon by [[Athletic Bilbao B|the reserves]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] and by the end of the same month had played his first match and scored his first goals at that level; he spent the campaign alternating between both squads.\n\nAt the start of [[2014\u201315 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2014\u201315]], Williams scored a [[hat-trick]] for Bilbao Athletic in a 4\u20130 win over [[SD Amorebieta]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bizkaia.eldesmarque.com/athletic-club/noticias/41860-williams-con-tres-goles-abandera-a-un-letal-bilbao-athletic|title=Williams, con tres goles, abandera a un letal Bilbao Athletic|trans-title=Williams, with three goals, spearheads a lethal Bilbao Athletic|publisher=El Desmarque|first=Javi|last=Beltr\u00e1n|language=es|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> and followed this on 7 September 2014 with another treble in a 5\u20131 rout of [[SD Leioa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/es/news/21/fichajes/2014/09/10/5096033/el-athletic-comienza-el-blindaje-de-i%C3%B1aki-williams|title=El Athletic comienza el blindaje de I\u00f1aki Williams|trans-title=Athletic start shielding I\u00f1aki  Williams|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Gorka|last=Posada|language=es|date=10 September 2014|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> Despite only playing the first half of the season, his 13 goals from 18 appearances helped the team ascend to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]].\n\nOn 6 December 2014, after profiting from [[Aritz Aduriz]]'s injury,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2014/12/05/primera/1417747514_009714.html|title=V\u00eda libre para el joven I\u00f1aki Williams por la lesi\u00f3n de Aduriz|trans-title=Freeway to young I\u00f1aki Williams due to Aduriz's injury|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Nika|last=Cuenca|language=es|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> Williams made his first-team \u2013 and [[La Liga]] \u2013 debut, starting in a 0\u20131 home loss against [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/primera/jornada_14/ath_cor/|title=Ghilas devuelve la sonrisa al C\u00f3rdoba|trans-title=Ghilas brings the smiles back to C\u00f3rdoba|newspaper=Marca|first=Jes\u00fas Fernando|last=L\u00f3pez|language=es|date=6 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> He netted his first goal on 19 February of the following year, starting and contributing to a [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League|2\u20132 draw]] at [[Torino F.C.]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]] [[Single-elimination tournament|round of 32]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000588/match=2014576/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Honours even between Torino and Athletic|publisher=UEFA|date=19 February 2015|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> becoming in the process the [[Athletic Bilbao signing policy|first black player to score for the club]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11827/9723739/inaki-williams-becomes-first-black-athletic-bilbao-goalscorer-in-117-year-history|title=Inaki Williams becomes first black Athletic Bilbao goalscorer in 117-year history|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=20 February 2015|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2015, Williams scored his first goal in the top flight, netting a [[Last-minute goal|last-minute]] winner in a 3\u20132 away success over [[Elche CF]] to help Athletic come from behind 0\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/la-liga/jornada_37/elc_ath/|title=Williams se\u00f1ala a Europa|trans-title=Williams points to Europe|newspaper=Marca|first=Jaime|last=Rinc\u00f3n|language=es|date=17 May 2015|accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref> Thirteen days later, he headed a consolation goal in the 1\u20133 loss to [[FC Barcelona]] in [[2015 Copa del Rey Final|the final]] of the [[Copa del Rey]] at the [[Camp Nou]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/may/30/athletic-bilbao-barcelona-copa-del-rey-final-match-report|title=Lionel Messi double gives Barcelona Cup final win over Athletic Bilbao|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=[[Sid Lowe|Sid]]|last=Lowe|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams scored a brace before giving away a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in Athletic's 3\u20131 win away to [[Real Betis]], on 1 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/williams-fires-improving-bilbao-to-victory-at-betis_sto4974994/story.shtml|title=Williams fires improving Bilbao to victory at Betis|publisher=Eurosport|accessdate=1 November 2015|date=1 November 2015}}</ref> He repeated the feat the following match, at home against [[FK Partizan]] in the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Europa League|Europa League group stage]] (5\u20131).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000658/match=2017018/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Williams at the double as Athletic go clear|publisher=UEFA|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> Finding the net in his third match running, he scored \"a phenomenal volley\" to help beat [[RCD Espanyol]] 2\u20131 at the [[San Mam\u00e9s Stadium (2013)|San Mam\u00e9s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11827/10060918/inaki-williams-scores-phenomenal-volley-for-athletic-bilbao-against-espanyol|title=Inaki Williams scores phenomenal volley for Athletic Bilbao against Espanyol|publisher=Sky Sports|date=8 November 2015|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SM-AB 2018 (12) (cropped).jpg |thumb|left|Williams playing for Athletic Bilbao in 2018]]\nIn late January 2016, having been scouted by the likes of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], Williams agreed to an extension of his contract until 2021. The deal included a \u20ac50 million [[buyout clause]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jan/21/inaki-williams-athletic-bilbao-new-contract|title=Athletic Bilbao\u2019s I\u00f1aki Williams signs new contract with \u20ac50m release clause|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Ed|last=Aarons|date=21 January 2016|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref> He was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] on 6 February at the end of a goalless home draw with [[Villarreal CF]], together with opponent [[Daniele Bonera]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-spain-idUKKCN0VF0P8|title=Torres grabs 100th Atletico goal in win over Eibar|publisher=[[Reuters]]|first=Rex|last=Gowar|date=6 February 2016|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring autumn 2017, Williams scored important late goals in the Europa League against [[\u00d6stersunds FK]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/stersunds-athletic-bilbao-europa-league-graham-potter-last-english-coach-in-europe-a8031991.html|title=An English coach in Europe: Graham Potter on his Swedish renaissance with \u00d6stersunds|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=Simon|last=Hughes|date=2 November 2017|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref> and [[Hertha BSC]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/athletic-bilbao-hertha-berlin-europa-league-line-ups-stats-live-blog-laporte-464372.jsp|title=Hertha Berlin suffer costly Europa League defeat to Bilbao|publisher=[[Bundesliga]]|date=23 November 2017|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref> to help his team finish top of [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League group stage#Group J|the group]]. On 17 January 2018, he agreed a contract renewal, running until 2025 with an incremental buyout clause of around \u20ac80 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/18655/inaki-williamss-contract-renewal.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams's contract renewal|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 January 2019, Williams scored both goals in a 2\u20130 home [[2018\u201319 La Liga|league]] win over [[Sevilla FC]], finding the net at San Mam\u00e9s for the first time in 41 league appearances (the previous occasion being in December 2016).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2019/01/13/primera/1547400351_943004.html|title=Williams desencadenado|trans-title=Williams unleashed|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Alfonso|last=Herr\u00e1n|language=es|date=13 January 2019|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> His second, involving a turn and sprint from his own half, touch away from the goalkeeper and precise finish at high speed, was described as \"incredible\" \u2013 he earned the [[Marca (newspaper)|''Marca'']] Golden Goal of the season for this strike.<ref name=Vooosh>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2019/jan/14/vooooooosh-inaki-williams-and-a-run-like-nobody-has-run-before|title='Vooooooosh': I\u00f1aki Williams and a run like nobody has run before|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Sid|last=Lowe|date=14 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=GOTS>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2019/12/16/5df79e0d22601de02c8b462f.html|title=The MARCA 2019 football awards: Messi collects sixth Pichichi|newspaper=Marca|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> The fixture was also his 100th successive appearance in the league,<ref name=Vooosh/> only the fifth Athletic player to achieve this<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/2019/01/13/inaki-williams-100-games-in-league|title=I\u00f1aki Williams, 100 games in League|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=13 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref> and the first outfield player from any Spanish club to do so since [[Fran (Spanish footballer)|Fran]] in 1993; for his performances, he was named the La Liga Player of the Month.<ref name=POTM19>{{cite web|url=https://www.laliga.es/en/news/inaki-williams-named-laliga-santander-player-of-the-month-for-january|title=I\u00f1aki Williams named LaLiga Santander Player of the Month for January|publisher=[[La Liga]]|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=7 February 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124147/https://www.laliga.es/en/news/inaki-williams-named-laliga-santander-player-of-the-month-for-january|archive-date=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nWilliams signed a nine-year contract in August 2019, with his release clause set at \u20ac135 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49316537|title=Inaki Williams: Athletic Bilbao striker signs nine-year contract|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 August 2019|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Late in the same month he started and scored in a 2\u20130 [[Basque derby]] win<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/cronica/2019/08/31/5d69a26b268e3ede538b4657.html|title=Athletic Club maul Real Sociedad in Basque derby|newspaper=Marca|first=Juan Carlos|last=D\u00edaz|date=31 August 2019|accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> for his 122nd consecutive Spanish League game, setting a new record by an outfield player in the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://football24.ua/sevilya_na_vlasnomu_poli_ne_zmogla_vtrimati_peremogu_nad_seltoyu_3_y_tur_primeri_matchi_pyatnitsi_n554959/|title=\u0410\u0442\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0456\u043a \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044f\u043a\u0438 \u0448\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u0443 \u0420\u0430\u0443\u043b\u044f \u0413\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0456\u0457 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0456\u0433 \u0420\u0435\u0430\u043b \u0421\u043e\u0441\u044c\u0454\u0434\u0430\u0434 \u2013 \u0406\u043d\u044c\u044f\u043a\u0456 \u0412\u0456\u043b\u044c\u044f\u043c\u0441 \u043e\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0432 \u0444\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0434|trans-title=Athletic defeated Real Sociedad with Raul Garc\u00eda masterpiece \u2013 Fantastic record for I\u00f1aki Williams|publisher=Football24 UA|language=ru|date=31 August 2019|accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> On 24 November, he repeated the feat in a 2\u20131 away victory against [[CA Osasuna]], breaking a 31\u2013game undefeated streak of the hosts at their [[El Sadar Stadium]]; the occasion also marked his 133rd consecutive appearance in the Spanish top level, establishing a new club record (previously held by [[Carmelo Cedr\u00fan]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insideathletic.com/2019/11/24/osasuna-1-2-athletic-club-lions-break-el-sadar/|title=Osasuna 1\u20132 Athletic Club: Lions break El Sadar|publisher=Inside Athletic|date=24 November 2019|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldesmarque.com/bizkaia/athletic-club/232808-inaki-williams-supera-el-record-historico-de-carmelo|title=I\u00f1aki Williams supera el r\u00e9cord hist\u00f3rico de Carmelo|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams breaks Carmelo's historical record|publisher=El Desmarque|first=As\u00eds|last=Mart\u00edn|language=es|date=24 November 2019|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 20 March 2015, Williams received his first international call-up, being named in [[Albert Celades]]' [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21]] squad for [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] with [[Norway national under-21 football team|Norway]] and [[Belarus national under-21 football team|Belarus]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ccaa.elpais.com/ccaa/2015/03/20/paisvasco/1426862572_832130.html|title=Williams, a la sub-21|trans-title=Williams, to the under-21|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|language=es|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on the 26th against the former, [[Substitute (association football)|replacing]] goalscorer [[Munir El Haddadi]] at half-time of a 2\u20130 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win in [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sefutbol.com/en/report-spain-beats-norway-and-strengthens-team-2-0|title=Spain beats Norway and strengthens the team (2\u20130)|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|first=Antonio D.|last=Mu\u00f1oz|date=26 March 2015|accessdate=30 March 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328194045/http://www.sefutbol.com/en/report-spain-beats-norway-and-strengthens-team-2-0|archive-date=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was one of 11 stand-by players for [[Vicente del Bosque]]'s [[Spain national football team|Spain]] squad at [[UEFA Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/breaking-news-aduriz-beats-costa-102100255.html|title=Euro 2016: Costa and Mata dropped from Spain's provisional squad|publisher=[[Yahoo Sports]]|date=17 May 2016|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> Around the same time, he was also coveted by the [[Ghana national football team|Ghanaian national team]] by their Spanish [[Scout (sport)|scout]] [[Gerard Nus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/18232/black-stars/2016/05/02/23039212/gerard-nus-inaki-williams-could-play-for-ghana|title=Gerard Nus: Inaki Williams could play for Ghana|publisher=Goal|first=Prince|last=Narkortu Teye|date=2 May 2016|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> He made his debut for the former on 29 May, replacing fellow debutant [[Marco Asensio]] at the hour mark of a 3\u20131 friendly defeat of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/amistosos_seleccion/3/spa_bih/|title=Nolito endulza un duelo at\u00edpico|trans-title=Nolito sweetens an atypical duel|newspaper=Marca|first=Tom\u00e1s|last=Campos|language=es|date=29 May 2016|accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October 2018, Williams debuted for the [[Basque Country national football team|Basque representative side]], playing the full 90 minutes of a 4\u20132 win over [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] at the [[Mendizorrotza Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/athletic-bilbao/20181012/452312310455/euskal-selekzioa-martin-elustondo-yuri-berchiche-williams-venezuela.html|title=Mart\u00edn, Elustondo, Yuri y Williams juegan los 90 minutos|trans-title=Mart\u00edn, Elustondo, Yuri and Williams play for 90 minutes|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Endika|last=R\u00edo|language=es|date=12 October 2018|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliams' younger brother, Nico, is also a footballer and a forward. He too was brought up at Athletic Bilbao.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/athletic-bilbao/20190210/46341074569/nico-williams-inaki-athletic-juveniles.html|title=El hermano de I\u00f1aki Williams debuta con gol en el juvenil del Athletic|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams' brother debuts with goal for Athletic youths|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Endika|last=R\u00edo|language=es|date=10 February 2019|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was one of the stars of the [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime]] television documentary series ''Six Dreams'', recorded during the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/03/08/football/1520517172_303503.amp.html|title=Six Dreams: Amazon launch series following LaLiga stars lives|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Rafael|last=Garc\u00eda Dom\u00ednguez|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|8 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/inaki-williams-dannis/277682/|title=I\u00f1aki Williams|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=Bilbao>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/players/2233/williams.html|title=Williams|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|accessdate=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!League!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[CD Basconia|Basconia]]\n|[[2013\u201314 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group IV \u2013 Basque Country|2013\u201314]]\n|[[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|18||7||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||18||7\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!18!!7!!0!!0!!0!!0!!18!!7\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Athletic Bilbao B|Bilbao Athletic]]\n|[[2013\u201314 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B#Group 2|2013\u201314]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|14||8||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||8\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B#Group 2|2014\u201315]]\n|18||13||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||18||13\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!32!!21!!0!!0!!0!!0!!32!!21\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Athletic Bilbao]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Athletic Bilbao season|2014\u201315]]\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[La Liga]]\n|19||1||4||1||2||1||25||3\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Athletic Bilbao season|2015\u201316]]\n|25||8||5||3||7||2||37||13\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Athletic Bilbao season|2016\u201317]]\n|38||5||3||2||8||1||49||8\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Athletic Bilbao season|2017\u201318]]\n|38||7||1||0||13||3||52||10\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Athletic Bilbao season|2018\u201319]]\n|38||13||3||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||41||15\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Athletic Bilbao season|2019\u201320]]\n|27||6||7||3{{efn|name=cup20|The Athletic Bilbao website<ref name=Bilbao/> credits Williams with one additional goal against FC Barcelona in the [[2019\u201320 Copa del Rey]] quarter-final, as initially reported in several media reports of the fixture;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51407354|title=Athletic Bilbao 1\u20130 Barcelona|publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020\u200e}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/cronica/2020/02/06/5e3c8e6d46163f9b898b4620.html|title=Barcelona fall to Athletic at the death|newspaper=Marca|first=Arch|last=Bell|date=6 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020\u200e}}</ref> however, it was recorded in the official match report as a [[Sergio Busquets]] own goal,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laliga.com/partido/temporada-2019-2020-copa-del-rey-athletic-club-fc-barcelona-5|title=Athletic Club 1\u20130 FC Barcelona|publisher=[[La Liga]]|language=es|date=6 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020\u200e}}</ref> with video footage of the incident inconclusive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4G1HT35TtTk?t=2m12|title=Copa del Rey | Cuartos de final | Athletic Club 1\u20130 FC Barcelona|trans-title=King's Cup | Quarter-finals | Athletic Club 1\u20130 FC Barcelona|publisher=[[YouTube]]|language=es|date=6 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020\u200e}}</ref>}}||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||34||9{{efn|name=cup20}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!185!!40!!23!!11{{efn|name=cup20}}!!30!!7!!238!!58{{efn|name=cup20}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!235!!68!!23!!11{{efn|name=cup20}}!!30!!7!!288!!86{{efn|name=cup20}}\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Spain U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] runner-up: [[2017 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2017]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40451698|title=Germany U21 1\u20130 Spain U21|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 June 2017|accessdate=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[La Liga Player of the Month]]: [[2018\u201319 La Liga|January 2019]]<ref name=POTM19/>\n*Golden Goal of the Season: 2018\u201319<ref name=GOTS/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Afro-Spaniard]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Athletic Bilbao profile|id=2233/williams}}\n*{{BDFutbol|202397}}\n*{{NFT|64459}}\n\n{{Athletic Bilbao squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Inaki}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Ghanaian descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bilbao]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:CD Basconia footballers]]\n[[Category:Bilbao Athletic footballers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque Country international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|Williams|Arthuer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = I\u00f1aki Williams\n| image = File:3 de diciembre 2015 Bienvenida al Atlethic de Bilbao 11 (23388774212) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Williams in 2015\n| fullname = I\u00f1aki Williams Arthuer\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1994|6|15|df=y}}<ref name=Bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/inaki-williams_prs413750/person.shtml|title=I\u00f1aki Williams|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Bilbao]], Spain<ref name=Bio/>\n| height = 1.86 m<ref name=Bio/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Athletic Bilbao]]\n| clubnumber = 9\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Nataci\u00f3n Pamplona\n| youthyears2 = 2009\u20132012 | youthclubs2 = [[CD Pamplona|Pamplona]]\n| youthyears3 = 2012\u20132013 | youthclubs3 = [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|Athletic Bilbao]]\n| years1 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs1 = [[CD Basconia|Basconia]] | caps1 = 18 | goals1 = 7\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs2 = [[Athletic Bilbao B|Bilbao Athletic]] | caps2 = 32 | goals2 = 21\n| years3 = 2014\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] | caps3 = 185 | goals3 = 40\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\u20132017 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 17 | nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2016\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2018\u2013 | nationalteam3 = [[Basque Country national football team|Basque Country]] | nationalcaps3 = 1 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| club-update = 11:20, 9 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 12 October 2018\n}}\n\n'''I\u00f1aki Williams Arthuer''' ({{IPA-eu|i\u0272aki wilians\u033a|lang}}; {{IPA-es|i\u02c8\u0272aki \u02c8wiljans|lang}}; born 15 June 1994) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Athletic Bilbao]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://larepublica.es/2015/05/07/inaki-williams-la-pantera-de-lezama/|title=I\u00f1aki Williams, la pantera de Lezama|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams, Lezama's panther|newspaper=La Rep\u00fablica|first=\u00cd\u00f1igo|last=Renedo|language=es|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=16 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812064446/http://larepublica.es/2015/05/07/inaki-williams-la-pantera-de-lezama/|archivedate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Bilbao]], [[Biscay]] to Ghanaian parents (that crossed the desert on foot and jumped the [[Melilla border fence]] to reach Spain),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://athletic.elcorreo.com/inaki-williams-millones-20190514070954-nt.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams: \u00abTengo entre 5 y 10 millones de euros\u00bb|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams: \"I have between 5 and 10 million euros\"|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|first=Silvia|last=Cantera|language=es|date=14 May 2019|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref> Williams spent much of his childhood in [[Pamplona]]<ref name=Correo>{{cite news|url=http://www.elcorreo.com/vizcaya/v/20131015/deportes/mas-baloncesto/inaki-williams-regresa-20131015.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams regresa con gol|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams returns with a goal|newspaper=El Correo|language=es|date=15 October 2013|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://athletic.elcorreo.com/discurso-williams-viral-negro-vasco-20180809175944-nt.html|title=El discurso de Williams que todo el mundo elogia: \u00abSoy negro, pero tambi\u00e9n vasco\u00bb|trans-title=The Williams speech that everyone praises: \"I am black, but also Basque\"|newspaper=El Correo|language=es|date=9 August 2018|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> and was playing youth football with local [[CD Pamplona]] when he was spotted by [[Athletic Bilbao]], who signed him to their youth setup at [[Lezama Facilities|Lezama]] at the age of 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.naiz.eus/es/blogs/marakanatxikia/posts/black-is-basque|title=Black is Basque|newspaper=Naiz|language=es|date=21 January 2016|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> He spent his first season with the ''[[Athletic Bilbao Juvenil|Juvenil A]]'' side and made a big impression, scoring at the rate of almost a goal a game (eventually ending with 36); the team [[2013 Copa del Rey Juvenil|finished runners-up]] in the [[Copa del Rey Juvenil de F\u00fatbol]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/06/29/futbol/cantera/1372536912.html|title=El Madrid gana la Copa juvenil veinte a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s|trans-title=Madrid win the 'Copa Juvenil' after 20 years|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=29 June 2013|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref> and on 25 June 2013 he signed a new contract with the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] club, running until 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2013/06/25/primera/1372176628_898059.html|title=El Athletic blinda a una de sus joyas del juvenil: I\u00f1aki Williams|trans-title=Athletic shield one of their youth squad gems: I\u00f1aki Williams|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Nika|last=Cuenca|language=es|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWilliams began [[2013\u201314 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2013\u201314]] playing with [[CD Basconia]], the [[farm team]] who competed in [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]. After suffering a knee injury in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://athletic.elcorreo.com/noticias/2013-08-15/inaki-williams-meses-baja-20130815.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams, de 2 a 5 meses de baja|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams, from 2 to 5 months out|newspaper=El Correo|language=es|date=15 August 2013|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> he returned to activity in October, made his debut as a senior and marked it with a goal.<ref name=Correo/> He was immediately called upon by [[Athletic Bilbao B|the reserves]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] and by the end of the same month had played his first match and scored his first goals at that level; he spent the campaign alternating between both squads.\n\nAt the start of [[2014\u201315 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2014\u201315]], Williams scored a [[hat-trick]] for Bilbao Athletic in a 4\u20130 win over [[SD Amorebieta]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bizkaia.eldesmarque.com/athletic-club/noticias/41860-williams-con-tres-goles-abandera-a-un-letal-bilbao-athletic|title=Williams, con tres goles, abandera a un letal Bilbao Athletic|trans-title=Williams, with three goals, spearheads a lethal Bilbao Athletic|publisher=El Desmarque|first=Javi|last=Beltr\u00e1n|language=es|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> and followed this on 7 September 2014 with another treble in a 5\u20131 rout of [[SD Leioa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/es/news/21/fichajes/2014/09/10/5096033/el-athletic-comienza-el-blindaje-de-i%C3%B1aki-williams|title=El Athletic comienza el blindaje de I\u00f1aki Williams|trans-title=Athletic start shielding I\u00f1aki  Williams|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Gorka|last=Posada|language=es|date=10 September 2014|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> Despite only playing the first half of the season, his 13 goals from 18 appearances helped the team ascend to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]].\n\nOn 6 December 2014, after profiting from [[Aritz Aduriz]]'s injury,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2014/12/05/primera/1417747514_009714.html|title=V\u00eda libre para el joven I\u00f1aki Williams por la lesi\u00f3n de Aduriz|trans-title=Freeway to young I\u00f1aki Williams due to Aduriz's injury|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Nika|last=Cuenca|language=es|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> Williams made his first-team \u2013 and [[La Liga]] \u2013 debut, starting in a 0\u20131 home loss against [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/primera/jornada_14/ath_cor/|title=Ghilas devuelve la sonrisa al C\u00f3rdoba|trans-title=Ghilas brings the smiles back to C\u00f3rdoba|newspaper=Marca|first=Jes\u00fas Fernando|last=L\u00f3pez|language=es|date=6 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> He netted his first goal on 19 February of the following year, starting and contributing to a [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League|2\u20132 draw]] at [[Torino F.C.]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]] [[Single-elimination tournament|round of 32]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000588/match=2014576/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Honours even between Torino and Athletic|publisher=UEFA|date=19 February 2015|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> becoming in the process the [[Athletic Bilbao signing policy|first black player to score for the club]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11827/9723739/inaki-williams-becomes-first-black-athletic-bilbao-goalscorer-in-117-year-history|title=Inaki Williams becomes first black Athletic Bilbao goalscorer in 117-year history|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=20 February 2015|accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2015, Williams scored his first goal in the top flight, netting a [[Last-minute goal|last-minute]] winner in a 3\u20132 away success over [[Elche CF]] to help Athletic come from behind 0\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/la-liga/jornada_37/elc_ath/|title=Williams se\u00f1ala a Europa|trans-title=Williams points to Europe|newspaper=Marca|first=Jaime|last=Rinc\u00f3n|language=es|date=17 May 2015|accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref> Thirteen days later, he headed a consolation goal in the 1\u20133 loss to [[FC Barcelona]] in [[2015 Copa del Rey Final|the final]] of the [[Copa del Rey]] at the [[Camp Nou]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/may/30/athletic-bilbao-barcelona-copa-del-rey-final-match-report|title=Lionel Messi double gives Barcelona Cup final win over Athletic Bilbao|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=[[Sid Lowe|Sid]]|last=Lowe|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams scored a brace before giving away a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in Athletic's 3\u20131 win away to [[Real Betis]], on 1 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/williams-fires-improving-bilbao-to-victory-at-betis_sto4974994/story.shtml|title=Williams fires improving Bilbao to victory at Betis|publisher=Eurosport|accessdate=1 November 2015|date=1 November 2015}}</ref> He repeated the feat the following match, at home against [[FK Partizan]] in the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Europa League|Europa League group stage]] (5\u20131).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000658/match=2017018/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Williams at the double as Athletic go clear|publisher=UEFA|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> Finding the net in his third match running, he scored \"a phenomenal volley\" to help beat [[RCD Espanyol]] 2\u20131 at the [[San Mam\u00e9s Stadium (2013)|San Mam\u00e9s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11827/10060918/inaki-williams-scores-phenomenal-volley-for-athletic-bilbao-against-espanyol|title=Inaki Williams scores phenomenal volley for Athletic Bilbao against Espanyol|publisher=Sky Sports|date=8 November 2015|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SM-AB 2018 (12) (cropped).jpg |thumb|left|Williams playing for Athletic Bilbao in 2018]]\nIn late January 2016, having been scouted by the likes of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], Williams agreed to an extension of his contract until 2021. The deal included a \u20ac50 million [[buyout clause]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jan/21/inaki-williams-athletic-bilbao-new-contract|title=Athletic Bilbao\u2019s I\u00f1aki Williams signs new contract with \u20ac50m release clause|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Ed|last=Aarons|date=21 January 2016|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref> He was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] on 6 February at the end of a goalless home draw with [[Villarreal CF]], together with opponent [[Daniele Bonera]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-spain-idUKKCN0VF0P8|title=Torres grabs 100th Atletico goal in win over Eibar|publisher=[[Reuters]]|first=Rex|last=Gowar|date=6 February 2016|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring autumn 2017, Williams scored important late goals in the Europa League against [[\u00d6stersunds FK]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/stersunds-athletic-bilbao-europa-league-graham-potter-last-english-coach-in-europe-a8031991.html|title=An English coach in Europe: Graham Potter on his Swedish renaissance with \u00d6stersunds|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=Simon|last=Hughes|date=2 November 2017|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref> and [[Hertha BSC]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/athletic-bilbao-hertha-berlin-europa-league-line-ups-stats-live-blog-laporte-464372.jsp|title=Hertha Berlin suffer costly Europa League defeat to Bilbao|publisher=[[Bundesliga]]|date=23 November 2017|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref> to help his team finish top of [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League group stage#Group J|the group]]. On 17 January 2018, he agreed a contract renewal, running until 2025 with an incremental buyout clause of around \u20ac80 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/18655/inaki-williamss-contract-renewal.html|title=I\u00f1aki Williams's contract renewal|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 January 2019, Williams scored both goals in a 2\u20130 home [[2018\u201319 La Liga|league]] win over [[Sevilla FC]], finding the net at San Mam\u00e9s for the first time in 41 league appearances (the previous occasion being in December 2016).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2019/01/13/primera/1547400351_943004.html|title=Williams desencadenado|trans-title=Williams unleashed|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Alfonso|last=Herr\u00e1n|language=es|date=13 January 2019|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> His second, involving a turn and sprint from his own half, touch away from the goalkeeper and precise finish at high speed, was described as \"incredible\" \u2013 he earned the [[Marca (newspaper)|''Marca'']] Golden Goal of the season for this strike.<ref name=Vooosh>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2019/jan/14/vooooooosh-inaki-williams-and-a-run-like-nobody-has-run-before|title='Vooooooosh': I\u00f1aki Williams and a run like nobody has run before|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Sid|last=Lowe|date=14 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=GOTS>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2019/12/16/5df79e0d22601de02c8b462f.html|title=The MARCA 2019 football awards: Messi collects sixth Pichichi|newspaper=Marca|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> The fixture was also his 100th successive appearance in the league,<ref name=Vooosh/> only the fifth Athletic player to achieve this<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/2019/01/13/inaki-williams-100-games-in-league|title=I\u00f1aki Williams, 100 games in League|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=13 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref> and the first outfield player from any Spanish club to do so since [[Fran (Spanish footballer)|Fran]] in 1993; for his performances, he was named the La Liga Player of the Month.<ref name=POTM19>{{cite web|url=https://www.laliga.es/en/news/inaki-williams-named-laliga-santander-player-of-the-month-for-january|title=I\u00f1aki Williams named LaLiga Santander Player of the Month for January|publisher=[[La Liga]]|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=7 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124147/https://www.laliga.es/en/news/inaki-williams-named-laliga-santander-player-of-the-month-for-january|archive-date=9 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWilliams signed a nine-year contract in August 2019, with his release clause set at \u20ac135 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49316537|title=Inaki Williams: Athletic Bilbao striker signs nine-year contract|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 August 2019|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Late in the same month he started and scored in a 2\u20130 [[Basque derby]] win<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/cronica/2019/08/31/5d69a26b268e3ede538b4657.html|title=Athletic Club maul Real Sociedad in Basque derby|newspaper=Marca|first=Juan Carlos|last=D\u00edaz|date=31 August 2019|accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> for his 122nd consecutive Spanish League game, setting a new record by an outfield player in the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://football24.ua/sevilya_na_vlasnomu_poli_ne_zmogla_vtrimati_peremogu_nad_seltoyu_3_y_tur_primeri_matchi_pyatnitsi_n554959/|title=\u0410\u0442\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0456\u043a \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0434\u044f\u043a\u0438 \u0448\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u0443 \u0420\u0430\u0443\u043b\u044f \u0413\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0456\u0457 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0456\u0433 \u0420\u0435\u0430\u043b \u0421\u043e\u0441\u044c\u0454\u0434\u0430\u0434 \u2013 \u0406\u043d\u044c\u044f\u043a\u0456 \u0412\u0456\u043b\u044c\u044f\u043c\u0441 \u043e\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0432 \u0444\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0434|trans-title=Athletic defeated Real Sociedad with Raul Garc\u00eda masterpiece \u2013 Fantastic record for I\u00f1aki Williams|publisher=Football24 UA|language=ru|date=31 August 2019|accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> On 24 November, he repeated the feat in a 2\u20131 away victory against [[CA Osasuna]], breaking a 31\u2013game undefeated streak of the hosts at their [[El Sadar Stadium]]; the occasion also marked his 133rd consecutive appearance in the Spanish top level, establishing a new club record (previously held by [[Carmelo Cedr\u00fan]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insideathletic.com/2019/11/24/osasuna-1-2-athletic-club-lions-break-el-sadar/|title=Osasuna 1\u20132 Athletic Club: Lions break El Sadar|publisher=Inside Athletic|date=24 November 2019|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldesmarque.com/bizkaia/athletic-club/232808-inaki-williams-supera-el-record-historico-de-carmelo|title=I\u00f1aki Williams supera el r\u00e9cord hist\u00f3rico de Carmelo|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams breaks Carmelo's historical record|publisher=El Desmarque|first=As\u00eds|last=Mart\u00edn|language=es|date=24 November 2019|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 20 March 2015, Williams received his first international call-up, being named in [[Albert Celades]]' [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21]] squad for [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] with [[Norway national under-21 football team|Norway]] and [[Belarus national under-21 football team|Belarus]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ccaa.elpais.com/ccaa/2015/03/20/paisvasco/1426862572_832130.html|title=Williams, a la sub-21|trans-title=Williams, to the under-21|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|language=es|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on the 26th against the former, [[Substitute (association football)|replacing]] goalscorer [[Munir El Haddadi]] at half-time of a 2\u20130 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win in [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sefutbol.com/en/report-spain-beats-norway-and-strengthens-team-2-0|title=Spain beats Norway and strengthens the team (2\u20130)|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|first=Antonio D.|last=Mu\u00f1oz|date=26 March 2015|accessdate=30 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328194045/http://www.sefutbol.com/en/report-spain-beats-norway-and-strengthens-team-2-0|archive-date=28 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was one of 11 stand-by players for [[Vicente del Bosque]]'s [[Spain national football team|Spain]] squad at [[UEFA Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/breaking-news-aduriz-beats-costa-102100255.html|title=Euro 2016: Costa and Mata dropped from Spain's provisional squad|publisher=[[Yahoo Sports]]|date=17 May 2016|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> Around the same time, he was also coveted by the [[Ghana national football team|Ghanaian national team]] by their Spanish [[Scout (sport)|scout]] [[Gerard Nus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/18232/black-stars/2016/05/02/23039212/gerard-nus-inaki-williams-could-play-for-ghana|title=Gerard Nus: Inaki Williams could play for Ghana|publisher=Goal|first=Prince|last=Narkortu Teye|date=2 May 2016|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> He made his debut for the former on 29 May, replacing fellow debutant [[Marco Asensio]] at the hour mark of a 3\u20131 friendly defeat of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/amistosos_seleccion/3/spa_bih/|title=Nolito endulza un duelo at\u00edpico|trans-title=Nolito sweetens an atypical duel|newspaper=Marca|first=Tom\u00e1s|last=Campos|language=es|date=29 May 2016|accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October 2018, Williams debuted for the [[Basque Country national football team|Basque representative side]], playing the full 90 minutes of a 4\u20132 win over [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] at the [[Mendizorrotza Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/athletic-bilbao/20181012/452312310455/euskal-selekzioa-martin-elustondo-yuri-berchiche-williams-venezuela.html|title=Mart\u00edn, Elustondo, Yuri y Williams juegan los 90 minutos|trans-title=Mart\u00edn, Elustondo, Yuri and Williams play for 90 minutes|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Endika|last=R\u00edo|language=es|date=12 October 2018|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliams' younger brother, Nico, is also a footballer and a forward. He too was brought up at Athletic Bilbao.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/athletic-bilbao/20190210/46341074569/nico-williams-inaki-athletic-juveniles.html|title=El hermano de I\u00f1aki Williams debuta con gol en el juvenil del Athletic|trans-title=I\u00f1aki Williams' brother debuts with goal for Athletic youths|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Endika|last=R\u00edo|language=es|date=10 February 2019|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was one of the stars of the [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime]] television documentary series ''Six Dreams'', recorded during the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/03/08/football/1520517172_303503.amp.html|title=Six Dreams: Amazon launch series following LaLiga stars lives|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Rafael|last=Garc\u00eda Dom\u00ednguez|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|8 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/inaki-williams-dannis/277682/|title=I\u00f1aki Williams|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=acprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/players/2233/williams.html|title=Williams|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|accessdate=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!League!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!